vectorData.altText: 20. The passage through the abdominal wall formed by the processus vaginalis, and ultimately, through which the testes pass to gain access to the scrotum is the _____________ _________________.
That's right!  The passage through the abdominal wall formed by the processus vaginalis is called the inguinal canal.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The passage through the abdominal wall formed by the processus vaginalis, and ultimately through which the testes pass on their way to the scrotum, is the inguinal canal. 
The point at which the testes pass from the extraperitoneal fascia through the transversalis fascia is called the deep inguinal ring. It is located just superior to the midpoint of the inguinal ligament. 
The point at which the tests pass through the external oblique aponeurosis into the superficial fascia of the abdominal wall is the superficial inguinal ring. It is superior to the inguinal ligament, at the pubis. 
The inguinal canal extends between these two landmarks. In the developed male, the spermatic cord remains within the inguinal canal.
The processus vaginalis, however, closes off from the peritoneal cavity, leaving an isolated sack of serous membrane, derived from the peritoneum, in the scrotum, called the tunica vaginalis testis.
